    ## âœ… 2. ì˜ì–´ ì •ë‹µ ëª©ë¡ (Answers Only)

    1. Casual dining has more of a percentage of consumers that are over \$100,000 in income.
    2. Double digit sales growth is simply much harder to come by when you're that big.
    3. Chiliâ€™s has played much better in the value realm, and in fact, quite astutely, Kevin Hochman and team have marketed to that relative value even versus fast food.
    4. The real test for Chiliâ€™s will be sustaining this recent growth for the long haul.
    5. Full service is not only the traffic conundrum getting people in the seats, but also then generating margin.
    6. Value offerings themselves typically aren't generating high margins.
    7. We have what's called a barbell strategy. So as long as we have items that we can offer for guests that want something a little bit more versus some guests that just want a high price point, and we keep that mix in balance, weâ€™re going to continue to grow profitability.
    8. On average, our franchisees invest about \$500,000 to open a Wingstop, and they're basically getting that entire investment paid back to them in less than two years because the income statement is so strong.
    9. Thereâ€™s no other brand at scale to the growth that Wingstopâ€™s doing.
    10. Its menu also lends itself well to an experiential offering for hanging out with friends or watching a football game.

